   <br>
Sometime in the near future, Earth is attacked by aliens who have been driven from their native planet by a rival faction. Their technology is only a little ahead of ours in relative terms, perhaps 50 years. In particular, they have fusion powered spacecraft and laser rockets but nothing fantastic or magical like ftl drive, hand held laser guns, or matter transmitters. <br>
<br>
The struggle settles into a stalemate, which the besieged US government seeks to break by building a gigantic Orion-type battleship. Much of the plot involves this top-secret effort, Project Archangel. At one point, a nosy reporter learns about the project. In the hope of advancing his career, he considers publishing the secret. This would allow the aliens to destroy the ship before it is ready for launch, thus eliminating humanity's last hope for preserving its independence. A former leader of the environmental movement learns about the reporter's intentions. Fortunately, the invasion has caused the eco-wacky to see the error of his ways. He promptly strangles the reporter and hides his body in a compost heap <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :lol --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/laugh.gif ALT=":lol"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  . The climax comes when the desperate Americans launch the Archangel ship, christened <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Michael</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END-->, and battle is joined high above the Earth.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> Footfall</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> presents the history and technology of Orion in detail and with great accuracy. This is probably the work of co-author Jerry Pournelle, a long-time advocate of nuclear energy in general and space applications in particular.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/uprojectorion.showPublicProfile?language=EN>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br>  Posts: 69<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(1/14/02 5:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm6.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=2.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.fas.org/nuke/hew/Usa/Tests/Rwmohawk2.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Footfall and Orion</span><hr size=1> This is the only story I have read involving Orion. Except for maybe Robert Heinleins 'Time for the Stars' which used a kind of fusion ship for interstellar travel sounding much like Orion. <br>
